webpackJsonp([1210],{"./node_modules/json-loader/index.js!./.cache/json/articles-javascript-javascript-for-loops-explained.json":function(e,o){e.exports={data:{markdownRemark:{html:'<p>The for statement creates a loop that consists of three optional expressions, enclosed in parentheses and separated by semicolons, followed by a statement or a set of statements executed in the loop.</p>\n<p>The for loop has the following syntax:</p>\n<pre><code>for ([initialization]; [condition]; [final-expression]) {  \n    code block to be executed                  \n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>[initialization] is executed before the loop (the code block) starts.</p>\n<p>[condition] defines the condition for running the loop (the code block).</p>\n<p>[final-expression] is executed each time after the loop (the code block) has been executed.</p>\n<h2>Example in JavaScript:</h2>\n<pre><code>var ourArray = [];\nfor (var i = 0; i &#x3C; 5; i++) {\n    ourArray.push(i);\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>From the example above, you can read:</p>\n<p>[initialization] sets a variable before the loop starts (var i = 0).</p>\n<p>[condition] defines the condition for the loop to run (i must be less than 5).</p>\n<p>[final-expression] increases a value (i++) each time the code block in the loop has been executed.</p>\n<h2>Why we need "for loops"?</h2>\n<p>For loops are used to loop through a block of code a known number of times. Sometimes it is the computer that knows how many times, not you, but it is still known.</p>\n<p>Checkout some of our other articles on loops:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://forum.freecodecamp.com/t/javascript-while-loop/14668">While Loop</a></li>\n<li><a href="http://forum.freecodecamp.com/t/javascript-for-in-loop/14665">For In Loop</a></li>\n</ul>',frontmatter:{title:"javaScript for Loops Explained",parent:"/home/stuart/guides/src/pages/articles/javascript/javascript-for-loops-explained/index.md absPath of file"}}},pathContext:{slug:"/articles/javascript/javascript-for-loops-explained/"}}}});
